<div class="post-date">Jul 30</div>
<h2><a https://yarnetsky.github.io/ontheriversedge/index.html?id=1114" title="May you live in interesting times"> May you live in interesting times</a></h2>

<div class="entry">


     

  	<p>Right now I feel like I was given one of those fortune cookies that read&#8212;&#8221;May you live in interesting times&#8221; or some such.</p>

	<p>Right now I&#8217;m in over my head with homework. In five weeks I&#8217;ve written more than 50 pages in papers and I have at least another dozen to go before I can quit next week. I think the last time I wrote that much in a short period of time was for our local paper during the 1997 flood.</p>

	<p>Either way, after this class I&#8217;ll be a third of the way toward a masters degree.</p>

	<p>Meanwhile, I have once again shuffled myself into the middle of a historic preservation hullabaloo as a member of the Madison Historic District Board of Review.</p>

	<p>A property owner pre-meditatively violated our historic district ordinance after we turned him down for vinyl windows on his 19th century industrial/commercial building. All of the sudden, my name&#8217;s been in the paper about every other day and on local online forums.</p>

	<p>The board is in a bad position. One one hand we have a very weak ordinance with no design guidelines. On the other our community has a strong libertarian streak where people don&#8217;t like to be told what to do with their properties. It amazes me that through all this some people seem to think we enjoy doing what we do.</p>

	<p>I&#8217;m learning to live with the notion I&#8217;ll be a punching bag for people&#8217;s views on preservation in Madison. However, I just hope people will continue allowing me to serve them in peace at the library (if that makes sense).</p>


 
<div class="line"></div>

